<br>
I'm outraged at these lawsuits:<br>
<br>
* $3B awarded to a smoker because Philip Morris didn't do enough to warn him of the dangers of smoking<br>
* A burglar in Southern California won a negligence lawsuit against a homeowner; there was water on the kitchen floor and the burglar slipped and fell.  He subsequently sued the homeowner and won monetary damages.<br>
* A McDonald's customer sued because through her clumsiness, she spilled hot coffee on herself.  The coffee was hot???  Oh my God!  Who would have thought!<br>
* A market downturn causes stocks to drop.  Immediately, all the class-action ambulance chasers quickly file class action lawsuits against every company whose stock dropped 5% or greater.  They have no plaintiffs, but file the cases anyway &quot;just in case&quot;.<br>
* The government suing tobacco companies on behalf of the people of the United States of America, claiming that we've all been swindled and that despite that plain-English warning on the packs that have existed since the 1960's, we were led to believe that smoking was good for our bodies?<br>
* The Department of Housing and Urban Development under Clinton/Gore suing gun manufacturers for creating the high crime rate in their low-income housing projects.  It's rather funny -- I went to a high school where 55% of the students were absent during shotgun deer season days, yet we didn't seem to have any gun crime problems.  But it's those evil gun manufacturers!<br>
<br>
The winners:  Lawyers, and only lawyers.<br>
The losers:  The public as a whole.  Lawsuit capabilities that exist today create far too much of a risk, prevent companies from entering markets, etc.<br>
<br>
So where do you draw the line?  How do you draw the line?  How do you ensure that remedies are available but at the same time control them?  1 person, $3 Billion in damages?  The guy's potential lifetime income probably came nowhere near $3M, much less a thousand times that.<br>
<br>
I'm all for ensuring that remedies are available as a last resort, but lawsuits today are just like the lottery.  Find something to sue for, and hope you hit it big!<br>
