<br>
Because companies like Netcom and such were pulling the plug on UNIX shell services in favor of direct PPP &amp; web, I decided to provide a service that was relatively stable for friends and people I thought I knew relatively well.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, the thanks I got was in the form of 2 subpoenas and 1 2703(d) (investigation order) for three different defendants (apparently I didn't know my acquaintances all that well) and had to retain counsel.  I wasn't happy with the fact I had to shell out thousands of dollars to provide assistance in investigations -- this wasn't even to defend myself -- all to the lawyers.<br>
<br>
Until the system is changed such that lawyers no longer are the only winners, the court system is more streamlined, the awards are more in-line with the damage done, and a common person can defend himself, I can't believe that suing is the right remedy for anything.<br>
<br>
It's very clear that the 12 jurors in the Philip Morris case were not thinking very clearly when they gave ONE PERSON an award of THREE BILLION DOLLARS.  That's a complete outrage, in my opinion.  How do you fix that?  No one wants to be judged if the outcome can be as unpredictable as that.  That's why required binding arbitration is becoming common in everything from employment agreements to software licensing.<br>
<br>
Note that I'm not a smoker, although I used to smoke cigarettes.<br>
<br>
