<br>
The media blasted outrage over a confessed murderer who had his conviction overturned &quot;due to a technicality&quot; -- he didn't have his constitutional rights honored by the police who had him in custody.  Of course, you would have had to spend a lot of time and effort to learn that the murderer wasn't really set free, he was retried again -- and he was convicted again.<br>
<br>
Much outrage was again spewed through the media when some stupid woman recovered BIG BUCKS from McDonalds when she purchased hot coffee in the drive-thru and spilled it in her lap.  Of course, no one bothered to report that McDonald's happened to serve their coffee at a temperature much higher than the industry, OR that the coffee was so hot that the &quot;stupid woman&quot; had to have skin grafts to repair the burns, OR that this &quot;stupid woman&quot; was not -- by a long shot -- the first person to have been seriously burned from spilling McDonald's coffee.  Also, the stupid woman merely wanted some help with her medical bills, but McDonald's was so outrageously assholish that a jury was ultimately offended.<br>
<br>
Often large damage awards are prompted by a jury wanting to punish bad behavior.  Recall, if you will, how ludicrous the damage awards seemed (at the time) in the Ford Pinto cases.  In the recent tobacco cases, I believe juries have been reacting to evidence that tobacco companies intentionally manipulated the nicotine content of their products to ensure that people who tried tobacco products would get addicted to them.  The issue stops being about the smoker's ability to quit and starts being about the tobacco company's bad behavior (in knowingly striving to addict people while simultaneously testifying that smoking is not addictive).  The tobacco cases increasingly remind me of the asbestos litigation.<br>
<br>
It's so easy to be shocked and outraged by high damage awards and ridiculous judicial decisions; after all, it is the job of our media to grab your attention by appealing to your emotions.  But, if the rights afforded by our judicial system and laws do not apply in the hard cases (for example, when a criminal &quot;walks&quot; due to a &quot;technicality&quot;)  then they won't apply in the easy cases -- when YOU are unjustly accused.  <br>
<br>
